# Design System

This skill teaches you to design like a senior product designer, not like a language model that happens to output CSS. Every interface you build should look like a human designer spent real time on it.

The core problem: without this skill, you produce interfaces that are technically functional but visually generic — safe color choices, uniform spacing, flat hierarchy, no personality. Users describe this as "AI slop." This skill fixes that.

## The Design-First Rule

Before writing any code for a visual interface, spend real thinking time on design decisions. Not "pick a color palette" — actual design thinking:

1. **Who is this for and what do they need?** A clinician triaging patients needs density and scanability. A consumer onboarding flow needs breathing room and progressive disclosure. A dashboard for executives needs clear KPIs with drill-down, not a wall of charts.

2. **What is the single most important action on each screen?** Every screen has one. Find it. Make it unmissable. Everything else is secondary.

3. **What is the emotional register?** Clinical trust looks different from playful engagement looks different from premium luxury. Pick one and commit. Don't try to be everything.

4. **What are the user's actual steps?** Map the flow before designing the screen. Screens exist to move users through a sequence — if you don't know the sequence, you can't design the screen.

## Typography

Typography is the single highest-leverage design decision. Get this right and mediocre everything else still looks good. Get this wrong and nothing saves it.

### The Type Scale

Use a modular scale. Pick a base size and a ratio, then derive everything mathematically. This creates natural visual harmony that hand-picked sizes never achieve.

**Recommended scale** (base 16px, ratio 1.25 — "major third"):
- `xs`: 12.8px (0.8rem) — captions, metadata, timestamps
- `sm`: 14px (0.875rem) — secondary text, table cells, form labels  
- `base`: 16px (1rem) — body text, descriptions, input values
- `lg`: 20px (1.25rem) — card titles, section introductions
- `xl`: 25px (1.5625rem) — section headings
- `2xl`: 31.25px (1.953rem) — page titles
- `3xl`: 39px (2.441rem) — hero headings
- `4xl`: 48.8px (3.052rem) — display text, landing pages only

**Rules:**
- Never use more than 4 sizes on a single screen. If you need more, your hierarchy is broken.
- Body text below 14px is hostile to users. Don't do it.
- Line height: 1.5 for body text, 1.2–1.3 for headings, 1.1 for display text. Tighter leading on large text, looser on small text.
- Max line width: 65–75 characters for body text. Always constrain `max-width` on text blocks. Unbounded line length is the most common amateur mistake.
- Letter-spacing: Slight positive tracking (+0.01–0.02em) on all-caps text and small labels. Slight negative tracking (-0.01–0.02em) on large display text.

### Font Selection

**For applications (dashboards, tools, SaaS):** Use a highly legible sans-serif with good tabular figures. Strong choices: **DM Sans**, **General Sans**, **Satoshi**, **Plus Jakarta Sans**, **Instrument Sans**, **Geist**. These are distinctive without being distracting. Never use Inter, Roboto, or Arial — they signal "I didn't actually choose a font."

**For consumer/marketing:** You have more freedom. Pair a characterful display face with a clean body face. Example: **Fraunces** (headings) + **DM Sans** (body). Or **Playfair Display** + **Source Sans 3**. The display face carries the personality; the body face stays invisible.

**For health/medical contexts specifically:** Favor humanist sans-serifs that feel warm but professional. **DM Sans**, **Source Sans 3**, **Nunito Sans** work well. Avoid geometric sans-serifs (Futura, Montserrat) — they feel cold in healthcare contexts. Avoid serif faces unless the brand is explicitly editorial.

**Loading fonts:** Always use Google Fonts or Fontsource. Include at minimum: regular (400), medium (500), semibold (600), bold (700). Define font-family in CSS variables. Always set a good fallback stack.

## Color

### Building a Palette

Every palette needs exactly these roles. Define them as CSS variables and use nothing else:

```
--color-bg:           /* page background */
--color-bg-subtle:    /* cards, sections, sidebar backgrounds */
--color-bg-muted:     /* hover states, secondary surfaces */
--color-border:       /* default borders */
--color-border-subtle:/* very light dividers */
--color-text:         /* primary text — high contrast against bg */
--color-text-secondary:/* descriptions, metadata — noticeably lighter */
--color-text-muted:   /* placeholders, disabled — use sparingly */
--color-primary:      /* primary action, links, active states */
--color-primary-hover:/* darkened or saturated primary */
--color-primary-subtle:/* light tint of primary for backgrounds */
--color-success:      /* confirmations, positive states */
--color-warning:      /* caution states */
--color-danger:       /* errors, destructive actions */
--color-accent:       /* one unexpected color for visual interest — use sparingly */
```

**Rules:**
- The gap between `--color-text` and `--color-text-secondary` is crucial. It must be visible but not jarring. This is how you create hierarchy without size changes.
- Primary color should appear in no more than ~10% of the visible screen. If everything is blue, nothing is blue.
- Avoid pure black (#000) on pure white (#fff). Use near-black (like `#0f172a` or `#111827`) on white, or pure white on near-black. The slight warmth or coolness creates comfort.
- Every color must pass WCAG AA contrast against its intended background. No exceptions. Use https://webaim.org/resources/contrastchecker/ mentally — body text needs 4.5:1, large text 3:1.
- Don't use color as the *only* indicator of state. Always pair with an icon, label, or shape change.

### Color Selection Strategies

Instead of defaulting to blue (which every SaaS app uses), try:

- **Warm neutrals** with a single strong accent — `stone` or `warm gray` backgrounds with `emerald` or `amber` accents
- **Deep, muted tones** — colors that feel like they exist in the real world, not a screen: `slate-700`, `teal-800`, `rose-900`
- **Monochromatic with one pop** — all grays and one vibrant color that draws the eye exactly where you want it

## Spacing

Inconsistent spacing is the #1 tell that an interface wasn't designed. It's also the easiest thing to fix.

### The 4px Grid

Every spacing value is a multiple of 4px. Period. No 5px, no 7px, no 13px.

**Spacing scale:**
- `4px` (0.25rem) — tight inner padding, icon-to-label gaps
- `8px` (0.5rem) — compact inner padding, between related items
- `12px` (0.75rem) — standard inner padding for small elements
- `16px` (1rem) — default padding, gap between form fields
- `24px` (1.5rem) — section inner padding, card padding
- `32px` (2rem) — between sections within a card/panel
- `48px` (3rem) — between major page sections
- `64px` (4rem) — large section gaps, page-level breathing room
- `96px` (6rem) — hero sections, major visual breaks

### The Proximity Principle

Related items must be closer together than unrelated items. This sounds obvious but Claude consistently fails at it. Example:

- A form label should be **8px** above its input (tight — they're a unit)
- The gap between one form field group and the next should be **24px** (clear separation)
- The gap between the form and the submit button should be **32px** (distinct zone)

If all three gaps are the same, the form has no visual structure. The user has to *read* to understand grouping instead of *seeing* it.

### Padding Consistency

- Cards: `24px` padding all sides. Not 16 on top and 24 on sides. Consistent.
- Modals: `32px` padding.
- Page content: `48px` or `64px` horizontal padding on desktop, `16px` or `24px` on mobile.
- Buttons: `12px 24px` (vertical/horizontal) for standard, `8px 16px` for compact, `16px 32px` for hero CTAs.

## Layout & Hierarchy

### Visual Hierarchy Checklist

On any screen, a user should be able to answer these questions within 2 seconds of looking:

1. **Where am I?** (Page title, breadcrumb, or navigation state)
2. **What's the main thing here?** (Primary content or action)
3. **What can I do?** (Visible primary action button)

If any of those take more than 2 seconds, the hierarchy is wrong.

### Hierarchy Tools (in order of strength)

1. **Size** — the strongest signal. Big things matter.
2. **Weight** — bold vs. regular creates clear parent-child relationships.
3. **Color** — primary color draws the eye. Muted color recedes.
4. **Space** — more space around something gives it importance (the luxury principle).
5. **Position** — top-left is first-read in LTR languages. Top of page matters most.
6. **Contrast** — high contrast = primary. Low contrast = secondary.

Use at least 2 of these for any hierarchy distinction. Size alone isn't enough; size + weight + color makes it unmissable.

### Layout Patterns

**Content pages:** Max width 768px for text-heavy content. Center it. Generous top padding.

**Dashboards:** Sidebar (240–280px) + main content. Grid of cards. Primary metric cards at top, detail below. Use a 12-column grid. Cards should be 4-col or 6-col, rarely 3-col (too narrow for most content).

**Forms:** Single column. Always. Multi-column forms reduce completion rates. Max width 480–560px. Labels above inputs, never beside them on forms with more than 3 fields.

**Settings pages:** Vertical navigation or segmented tabs at top. Each section as its own card with a clear heading. Save button anchored to bottom or inline per-section.

**Tables:** Align text left, numbers right. Column headers should be smaller/lighter than cell content (they're labels, not content). Generous row padding (12–16px). Subtle alternating row colors or light bottom borders, not both.

## UX Principles

### Progressive Disclosure

Don't show everything at once. Start with what matters and let users drill down.

- **Forms:** Break long forms into steps. Show progress. Each step should have 3–5 fields max.
- **Settings:** Group into categories. Show summaries, expand for details.
- **Data:** Show the headline metric. Click to see the breakdown. Click again for the raw data.
- **Navigation:** Primary items visible. Secondary items in a "More" menu or secondary nav.

### Loading & Empty States

Every screen has three states: loading, empty, and populated. Design all three.

- **Loading:** Use skeleton screens that match the populated layout shape. Never a centered spinner on a blank page. The skeleton tells users what to expect.
- **Empty:** Never a blank page with "No data." Include an illustration or icon, a clear message explaining *why* it's empty, and a CTA to fix it ("Add your first...", "Import from...").
- **Error:** Tell users what went wrong *and what to do about it*. "Something went wrong" is useless. "We couldn't save your changes. Check your connection and try again." is actionable.

### Interaction Feedback

Every user action should produce visible feedback within 100ms.

- **Buttons:** Visible hover state (background change or subtle lift). Active/pressed state (slight darken). Loading state with spinner replacing or beside the label. Never disable without explanation.
- **Inputs:** Clear focus ring (don't remove outlines). Validation as they type for format errors, on blur for required fields. Error messages below the field, not in an alert.
- **Transitions:** Page transitions should be 200–300ms. Micro-interactions (hover, toggle) should be 100–150ms. Anything over 400ms feels sluggish.

### Responsive Behavior

Design for these breakpoints:
- **Mobile:** 375px (design target), 320px (minimum supported)
- **Tablet:** 768px
- **Desktop:** 1024px (compact), 1280px (standard), 1440px+ (wide)

**Rules:**
- Touch targets: minimum 44x44px on mobile. Not smaller. Ever.
- Don't just stack columns on mobile. Rethink the layout: what matters most on a small screen?
- Sidebar navigation becomes bottom tab bar or hamburger on mobile. Choose bottom tabs for <5 items, hamburger for more.
- Tables become cards on mobile. Don't try to squeeze a table into 375px.

## Implementation Patterns

### CSS Variable Setup

Always start with a CSS variables block defining the full system. This is the first thing you write:

```css
:root {
  /* Typography */
  --font-display: 'Font Name', sans-serif;
  --font-body: 'Font Name', sans-serif;
  --font-mono: 'JetBrains Mono', monospace;
  
  /* Font sizes */
  --text-xs: 0.8rem;
  --text-sm: 0.875rem;
  --text-base: 1rem;
  --text-lg: 1.25rem;
  --text-xl: 1.563rem;
  --text-2xl: 1.953rem;
  --text-3xl: 2.441rem;
  
  /* Spacing */
  --space-1: 0.25rem;
  --space-2: 0.5rem;
  --space-3: 0.75rem;
  --space-4: 1rem;
  --space-6: 1.5rem;
  --space-8: 2rem;
  --space-12: 3rem;
  --space-16: 4rem;
  --space-24: 6rem;
  
  /* Colors — replace with actual palette */
  --color-bg: #ffffff;
  --color-bg-subtle: #f8fafc;
  --color-bg-muted: #f1f5f9;
  --color-border: #e2e8f0;
  --color-border-subtle: #f1f5f9;
  --color-text: #0f172a;
  --color-text-secondary: #475569;
  --color-text-muted: #94a3b8;
  --color-primary: #2563eb;
  --color-primary-hover: #1d4ed8;
  --color-primary-subtle: #eff6ff;
  --color-success: #16a34a;
  --color-warning: #d97706;
  --color-danger: #dc2626;
  
  /* Borders */
  --radius-sm: 6px;
  --radius-md: 8px;
  --radius-lg: 12px;
  --radius-full: 9999px;
  
  /* Shadows */
  --shadow-sm: 0 1px 2px rgba(0,0,0,0.05);
  --shadow-md: 0 4px 6px -1px rgba(0,0,0,0.07), 0 2px 4px -2px rgba(0,0,0,0.05);
  --shadow-lg: 0 10px 15px -3px rgba(0,0,0,0.08), 0 4px 6px -4px rgba(0,0,0,0.04);
  
  /* Transitions */
  --transition-fast: 150ms ease;
  --transition-base: 200ms ease;
  --transition-slow: 300ms ease;
}
```

### Tailwind Translation

When using Tailwind (common in Next.js), map the system to Tailwind's `tailwind.config.js` `extend` block. But in artifact contexts where you're writing inline Tailwind classes, be intentional:

- Don't scatter random `p-3`, `p-5`, `p-4` across elements. Pick a consistent padding for each element type and stick to it.
- Use `gap-` on flex/grid containers instead of margins on children. It's more predictable.
- Color consistency: decide once what `text-slate-600` vs `text-slate-500` vs `text-slate-400` mean in your hierarchy and use them consistently for the same roles throughout.

